        "Chiaroscuro — the dramatic contrast between light and dark — is a form-rendering technique pioneered by Renaissance painters like Caravaggio and Leonardo da Vinci. By placing deeply shadowed areas against brightly lit surfaces, these artists created powerful illusions of volume and dramatic emotional intensity. Modern photographers, filmmakers, and illustrators continue to use chiaroscuro to direct attention, create mood, and sculpt form. In graphic design, understanding chiaroscuro helps designers evaluate photographic images and illustrations for their tonal impact and spatial clarity.",
        "The debate between skeuomorphism (design that mimics real-world objects and materials) and flat design (design that embraces two-dimensional abstraction) is fundamentally a debate about form. Skeuomorphic design uses rich shadows, textures, and highlights to make digital elements look and feel like physical objects — leather textures, metal knobs, wooden shelves. Flat design strips away these dimensional cues in favor of clean shapes, solid colors, and typographic hierarchy. Neither approach is inherently superior; each serves different purposes and audiences. The current trend toward semi-flat design (flat with subtle shadows and depth cues) represents a practical middle ground.",
