      example: "Ansel Adams' black-and-white landscape photographs demonstrate the extraordinary communicative power of value. Using his Zone System — a methodical approach to exposure and development that mapped the full range from pure black (Zone 0) to pure white (Zone X) — Adams created images with stunning depth, luminosity, and emotional impact using value alone. His work proves that color is not required for powerful visual communication; masterful control of light and dark is sufficient to create hierarchy, depth, mood, and breathtaking beauty.",
      detailedNotes: [
        "In color theory, every hue has an inherent value. Yellow is inherently light (high value), while blue and violet are inherently dark (low value). This means that two colors can appear vividly different in hue but nearly identical in value — creating what designers call an 'equiluminant' or 'vibrating' color combination. Red and green at equal value, for example, create a shimmering, uncomfortable visual effect because the eye cannot establish a clear figure-ground relationship. Designers must check value relationships independently of hue to avoid these accessibility and readability pitfalls.",
        "In digital interface design, value structure directly determines usability. Dark mode interfaces (light content on dark backgrounds) have gained popularity for reducing eye strain in low-light environments and saving battery on OLED screens. However, dark mode requires careful value calibration: pure white text (#FFFFFF) on pure black (#000000) creates harsh, tiring contrast. Professional dark themes use slightly desaturated light text (e.g., #E0E0E0) on very dark but not pure black backgrounds (e.g., #1A1A1A), softening the contrast to a comfortable reading level.",
        "Value thumbnail sketches — small, quick studies that map out a composition using only three to five value levels — are one of the most useful planning tools in design and illustration. By solving the value structure before addressing color, typography, or detail, designers ensure the composition's hierarchy and spatial relationships are clear from the start. This practice saves enormous time by catching structural problems early, before hours are invested in rendering details that would need to be reworked."
      ],
      important: "Value does the heavy lifting of visual communication. If a design does not work in grayscale — if the hierarchy collapses and elements merge — no amount of beautiful color will save it. Always establish strong value contrast before adding color.",
      tip: "Use your design software's desaturation or grayscale preview mode to check every composition. If the important elements remain clearly separated and the reading order is obvious in grayscale, your value structure is sound.",
      check: {
        question: "Why is it important to check a design in grayscale?",
        options: [
          "To make sure all the fonts are correctly installed",
          "To verify that the layout works on all screen sizes",
          "To ensure that value contrast is sufficient for hierarchy and legibility independent of color",
          "To reduce the file size before exporting"
        ],
        answer: 2,
        explanation: "Converting to grayscale strips away hue and saturation, revealing the value structure. If hierarchy and legibility are clear in grayscale, the design's communication foundation is strong — meaning it will work for colorblind users and in all viewing conditions."
      }
