        "Understanding color modes is essential for professional practice. RGB (Red, Green, Blue) is the color model for screens — light is emitted in combinations of these three channels. CMYK (Cyan, Magenta, Yellow, Key/Black) is the model for print — inks are layered on paper. A color created in RGB may look different in CMYK because the gamuts (range of reproducible colors) differ; vivid blues and neon greens that glow on screen often appear dull when printed. Spot colors (e.g., Pantone Matching System) provide a standardized ink-mixing system that ensures color consistency across print runs and vendors. Professional designers set the correct color mode from the start and use color profiles (ICC) to manage cross-device consistency.",
        "Color psychology — the study of how colors affect human behavior and perception — is frequently oversimplified in design education. Claims like 'blue makes people trust you' or 'red increases appetite' are based on real research but are highly context-dependent. A study showing that blue bank interfaces increase trust does not mean blue packaging increases food sales. Cultural context, personal experience, and the specific shade all influence color perception. Designers should use color psychology as a set of informed starting hypotheses, not as deterministic rules.",
